In EF Core 2.x, if you used a method EF couldn't translate (e.g., a custom `IsValid()` helper inside `Where`), EF would silently load all rows and evaluate the method in C#. This caused catastrophic performance bugs that were invisible until production.

EF Core 3.0 changed this to throw an exception, forcing developers to be explicit. If you need client evaluation, split the query:

```csharp
// Load filtered data from DB first
var rows = await ctx.Products
    .Where(p => p.CategoryId == id)  // translatable
    .ToListAsync();

// Then apply C#-only logic in memory
var filtered = rows.Where(p => MyCustomCheck(p)).ToList();
```

**Senior note:** Knowing this history helps explain why older EF Core tutorials sometimes show `.AsEnumerable()` mid-query. Always check generated SQL (via logging) to verify where evaluation actually happens.

