// Correct: translate what you can, then filter in memory
var orders = await ctx.Orders
    .Where(o => o.Status == OrderStatus.Active) // SQL
    .AsEnumerable()                              // boundary
    .Where(o => MyMethod(o.Name))               // C#
    .ToList();

answer.detail:
Loading full entity graphs when you only need two or three fields is one of the most common EF Core performance mistakes. A `SELECT *` on a table with BLOB columns or dozens of columns wastes network bandwidth and allocates large objects on the .NET heap.

```csharp
// Bad: loads all columns including LargeDescription, BinaryData, etc.
var products = await ctx.Products.Where(p => p.IsActive).ToListAsync();

// Good: only needed columns in SQL
var dtos = await ctx.Products
    .Where(p => p.IsActive)
    .Select(p => new ProductSummaryDto {
        Id = p.Id,
        Name = p.Name,
        Price = p.Price,
        TagCount = p.Tags.Count  // translated to SQL COUNT
    })
    .ToListAsync();
```

**Senior note:** Projections also decouple your API contract from your domain model. Using entity types directly in API responses leaks domain internals and can cause accidental lazy-load cycles during JSON serialization. Always project to DTOs at the service/query layer.

EF Core's internal query pipeline steps are: parse LINQ → build expression tree → translate to SQL → execute. The first three steps are cached per query shape, so repeated calls with different parameter values skip re-translation. However, the cache lookup itself has overhead (dictionary hash, expression comparison).

`EF.CompileAsyncQuery` removes even that overhead by producing a typed delegate at startup:

```csharp
private static readonly Func<AppDbContext, int, Task<User?>> GetUserById =
    EF.CompileAsyncQuery((AppDbContext ctx, int id) =>
        ctx.Users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Id == id));

// At call site — zero translation overhead
var user = await GetUserById(dbContext, userId);
```

**Senior note:** Benchmarks from the EF Core team show compiled queries are roughly 2-3x faster on hot paths compared to standard queries. But for most enterprise CRUD apps, the bottleneck is network/IO, not LINQ translation. Profile before optimizing.

