**Common mistake — parallel LINQ with shared context:**
```csharp
// WRONG: two async operations on same context concurrently
var task1 = ctx.Orders.CountAsync();
var task2 = ctx.Products.CountAsync();
await Task.WhenAll(task1, task2); // throws InvalidOperationException
```

EF Core detects this and throws: *"A second operation was started on this context instance before a previous operation completed."*

**Correct — sequential awaits or separate contexts:**
```csharp
// Sequential on same context (safe)
var orderCount = await ctx.Orders.CountAsync();
var productCount = await ctx.Products.CountAsync();

// Parallel with factory
await using var ctx1 = factory.CreateDbContext();
await using var ctx2 = factory.CreateDbContext();
var t1 = ctx1.Orders.CountAsync();
var t2 = ctx2.Products.CountAsync();
await Task.WhenAll(t1, t2);
```

**Senior note:** EF Core 7+ added improved concurrency detection messages. But the fundamental design is unit-of-work per logical operation — don't fight it with parallelism on a single context.

