**Why it matters:**
```csharp
// Both posts share the same Blog in the DB
var posts = await ctx.Posts.Include(p => p.Blog).ToListAsync();
bool sameInstance = ReferenceEquals(posts[0].Blog, posts[1].Blog); // true — identity resolution
```

Without identity resolution, you'd get two different `Blog` objects in memory representing the same row, and modifying one would not affect the other — leading to bugs where `SaveChanges()` misses changes made to one copy.

**No-tracking scenario:**
```csharp
// With AsNoTracking — two Blog instances for the same DB row
var posts = await ctx.Posts.Include(p => p.Blog).AsNoTracking().ToListAsync();
bool sameInstance = ReferenceEquals(posts[0].Blog, posts[1].Blog); // false!

// With AsNoTrackingWithIdentityResolution — fixed
var posts2 = await ctx.Posts.Include(p => p.Blog)
    .AsNoTrackingWithIdentityResolution().ToListAsync();
bool sameNow = ReferenceEquals(posts2[0].Blog, posts2[1].Blog); // true
```

**Senior note:** Identity resolution is one reason why a request-scoped DbContext is valuable — it acts as a first-level cache within the request boundary. Two calls to `FindAsync(42)` within the same context return the same instance without a second DB hit.

